# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-animations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-animations/api-animation] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] It’s been available across browsers since March 2020.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] The **`Animation`** interface of the Web Animations API represents a single animation player and provides playback controls and a timeline for an animation node or source.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Creates a new `Animation` object instance.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] The current time value of the animation in milliseconds, whether running or paused.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] If the animation lacks a `timeline`, is inactive or hasn't been played yet, its value is `null`.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Gets and sets the `AnimationEffect` associated with this animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] This will usually be a `KeyframeEffect` object.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Returns the current finished Promise for this animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Gets and sets the `String` used to identify the animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Returns a number between `0` and `1` indicating the animation's overall progress towards its finished state.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Indicates whether the animation is currently waiting for an asynchronous operation such as initiating playback or pausing a running animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Returns an enumerated value describing the playback state of an animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Gets or sets the playback rate of the animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Returns the current ready Promise for this animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Indicates whether the animation is active, has been automatically removed after being replaced by another animation, or has been explicitly persisted by a call to `Animation.persist()`.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Gets or sets the scheduled time when an animation's playback should begin.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Gets or sets the `timeline` associated with this animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Clears all `keyframeEffects` caused by this animation and aborts its playback.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Commits the current styling state of an animation to the element being animated, even after that animation has been removed.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] It will cause the current styling state to be written to the element being animated, in the form of properties inside a `style` attribute.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Seeks either end of an animation, depending on whether the animation is playing or reversing.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Explicitly persists an animation, preventing it from being automatically removed when another animation replaces it.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Starts or resumes playing of an animation, or begins the animation again if it previously finished.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Reverses playback direction, stopping at the start of the animation.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] If the animation is finished or unplayed, it will play from end to beginning.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Sets the speed of an animation after first synchronizing its playback position.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Fires when the `Animation.cancel()` method is called or when the animation enters the `"idle"` play state from another state.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Fires when the animation finishes playing.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Fires when the animation is automatically removed by the browser.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Blinking and flashing animation can be problematic for people with cognitive concerns such as Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD).
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Additionally, certain kinds of motion can be a trigger for Vestibular disorders, epilepsy, and migraine, and Scotopic sensitivity.
[src:web-animations/api-animation] Consider providing a mechanism for pausing or disabling animation, as well as using the Reduced Motion Media Query (or equivalent user agent client hint `Sec-CH-Prefers-Reduced-Motion`) to create a complimentary experience for users who have expressed a preference for no animated experiences.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] The **CSS animations** module lets you animate the values of CSS properties, such as background-position and transform, over time by using keyframes.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Each keyframe describes how the animated element should render at a given time during the animation sequence.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] You can use the properties in the animations module to control the duration, number of repetitions, delayed start, and other aspects of an animation.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] To view the animation in the box below, click the checkbox 'Play the animation' or hover the cursor over the box.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] When the animation is active, the cloud at the top changes shape, snowflakes fall, and the snow level at the bottom rises.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] To pause the animation, uncheck the checkbox or move your cursor away from the box.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] This sample animation uses `animation-iteration-count` to make the flakes fall repeatedly, `animation-direction` to make the cloud move back and forth, `animation-fill-mode` to raise the snow level in response to the cloud movement, and `animation-play-state` to pause the animation.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Click "Play" in the example above to see or edit the code for the animation in the MDN Playground.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Currently, no browsers support these features.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] All animations, even those with 0 seconds duration, throw animation events.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Step-by-step tutorial on how to create animations using CSS.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] This article describes the animation-related CSS properties and at-rule and how they interact with each other.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Overview of how different CSS properties can be animated, including their animation types and interpolation methods.
[src:web-animations/css-animations] Common animation requirements that can be solved with a few lines of JavaScript.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] It’s been available across browsers since September 2015.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] The **`@keyframes`** CSS at-rule controls the intermediate steps in a CSS animation sequence by defining styles for keyframes (or waypoints) along the animation sequence.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] This gives more control over the intermediate steps of the animation sequence than transitions.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] A case-sensitive `<custom-ident>` or string naming the keyframe list.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] A percentage through the animation sequence at which the specified keyframe should occur.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] A percentage through the specified `animation-range` at which the specified keyframe should occur.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] To use keyframes, create a `@keyframes` rule with a name that is then used by the `animation-name` property to match an animation to its keyframe declaration.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] Each `@keyframes` rule contains a style list of keyframe selectors, which specify percentages along the animation when the keyframe occurs, and a block containing the styles for that keyframe.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] You can list the keyframe percentages in any order; they will be handled in the order they should occur.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] JavaScript can access the `@keyframes` at-rule with the CSS object model interface `CSSKeyframesRule`.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] If a keyframe rule doesn't specify the start or end states of the animation (that is, `0%`/`from` and `100%`/`to`), browsers will use the element's existing styles for the start/end states.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] This can be used to animate an element from its initial state and back.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] Properties that can't be animated in keyframe rules are ignored, but supported properties will still be animated.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] If multiple keyframe sets exist for a given name, the last one encountered by the parser is used.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] `@keyframes` rules don't cascade, so animations never derive keyframes from more than one rule set.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] If a given animation time offset is duplicated, all keyframes in the `@keyframes` rule for that percentage are used for that frame.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] There is cascading within a `@keyframes` rule if multiple keyframes specify the same percentage values.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] Properties that aren't specified in every keyframe are interpolated if possible — properties that can't be interpolated are dropped from the animation.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] If a keyframe is defined multiple times but not all affected properties are in each keyframe, all values specified in these keyframes are considered.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] In this example, at the `50%` keyframe, the values used are `top: 10px` and `left: 20px`.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] Declarations in a keyframe qualified with the `important` flag set are ignored.
[src:web-animations/css-keyframes] See Using CSS animations and scroll-driven animations for examples.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] The **CSS transitions** module specifies functionality for creating gradual transitions between different CSS property values.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] The behavior of these transitions can be controlled by specifying their easing function, duration, and other values.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] Normally, when the value of a CSS property changes, the result of the change from the old value to the new value is immediate.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] The CSS transitions module enables controlling a progression from the old property state to the new state over a specified period of time.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] It also provides event handlers to allow code to be run in response to different stages of a transition being reached.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] In certain cases, there is no originating "from" value for a transition.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] For example, if an element gets added to the DOM, the styles defined are for the "to" state.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] This module provides the `@starting-style` at-rule, which enables defining starting styles for such cases.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] The module also defines how discrete property values should be transitioned, such as transitioning the discretely animated `display` property from the `none` value to a displayed value.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] Step-by-step tutorial explaining how to create transitions using CSS.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] This article describes each relevant CSS property and explains how they interact with each other.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] Transitioning to and from the `none` value of the discretely animated `display` property.
[src:web-animations/css-transitions] Examples of transitioning from `@starting-style` to final `:popover-open` and `:open` pseudo-class styles.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] The **`KeyframeEffect`** interface of the Web Animations API lets us create sets of animatable properties and values, called **keyframes.** These can then be played using the `Animation()` constructor.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Returns a new `KeyframeEffect` object instance, and also allows you to clone an existing keyframe effect object instance.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Gets and sets the element, or originating element of the pseudo-element, being animated by this object.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] This may be `null` for animations that do not target a specific element or pseudo-element.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Gets and sets the selector of the pseudo-element being animated by this object.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] This may be `null` for animations that do not target a pseudo-element.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Gets and sets the iteration composite operation for resolving the property value changes of this keyframe effect.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Gets and sets the composite operation property for resolving the property value changes between this and other keyframe effects.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Returns the calculated, current timing values for this keyframe effect.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Returns the computed keyframes that make up this effect along with their computed keyframe offsets.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Returns the object associated with the animation containing all the animation's timing values.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Replaces the set of keyframes that make up this effect.
[src:web-animations/keyframeeffect] Updates the specified timing properties.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] The **Web Animations API** allows for synchronizing and timing changes to the presentation of a Web page, i.e., animation of DOM elements.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] It does so by combining two models: the Timing Model and the Animation Model.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] The Web Animations API provides a common language for browsers and developers to describe animations on DOM elements.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] To get more information on the concepts behind the API and how to use it, read Using the Web Animations API.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Provides playback controls and a timeline for an animation node or source.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Can take an object created with the `KeyframeEffect()` constructor.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Describes sets of animatable properties and values, called **keyframes** and their timing options.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] These can then be played using the `Animation()` constructor.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] This interface exists to define timeline features (inherited by `DocumentTimeline` and future timeline objects) and is not itself accessed by developers.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Part of the CSS Animations module, capturing the animation name and elapsed time.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Represents animation timelines, including the default document timeline (accessed using the `Document.timeline` property).
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] The Web Animations API adds features to `document` and `element`.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] The `DocumentTimeline` object representing the default document timeline.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Returns an Array of `Animation` objects currently in effect on elements in the `document`.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] A shortcut method for creating and playing an animation on an element.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] It returns the created `Animation` object instance.
[src:web-animations/web-animations-api] Returns an Array of `Animation` objects currently affecting an element or which are scheduled to do so in the future.
